      "So self-empathy may also be reconstruction, where the present me takes traces from a past or hidden me and tries to rebuild that state inside the current system. This is not the same as self-understanding. I can explain myself very well and still not really be close to myself. I can say why I reacted that way, where the pattern came from, what experience shaped it, and turn it into a clean story, and yet the explanation can feel too far above the state, as if I have described the system from the outside without letting the older or hidden state become active again. I know it, but I have not met it. Self-empathy seems to require something else: letting another version of me produce a signal again, not fully returning to that state, which is impossible, but rebuilding enough of it to feel why it mattered from somewhere closer than explanation.",
      "This is where drawing, images, and something like a mandala start to make sense to me, and I do not mean this in a mystical way. I just think language sometimes moves too fast. The moment I put a state into words it becomes a reason, a story, a category, or a conclusion, which is useful, but language also organizes the state from the current point of view and can make something too clean too early. A drawing does not have to do that immediately. If I draw something about myself, or make a shape, a pattern, a set of colors, or a space, the state can come out without first becoming a sentence, appearing instead as crowded, empty, sharp, soft, repeated, broken, centered, heavy, unbalanced, or strangely calm.",
